TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$showHint = 3;

$c = 3*10**8;
$e = 1.6*10**-19;
$h = 6.63*10**-34;
$hbar = $h/(2*pi);

$mass = 5.89;
$massSI = $mass*10**-26;
$Uposition = sprintf("%0.2f", random(0.5,1,0.05));
$UpositionSI = $Uposition*10**-6;

$UvelocitySI = ($hbar/2)/($massSI*$UpositionSI);
$energySI = 0.5*($massSI*($UvelocitySI**2));
$energy = ($energySI/$e)*10**13;

Context() -> texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT 

$PAR
$PAR

<b>If you do not answer this question correctly in $showHint attempts, you can get a hint.</b>

$PAR
$PAR

a) If the position of a chlorine ion in a membrane is measured to an accuracy of \($Uposition\) <span style="font-family: 'Times'; font-size: 20px";>&mu;m</span>, what is its minimum uncertainty in velocity, given its mass is \($mass \times 10^{-26} \, \textrm{kg}\)?

$PAR
$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(\textrm{m/s}\)

$PAR
$PAR

END_TEXT
BEGIN_HINT
Can you rearrange Heisenberg's uncertainty principle to solve for the minimum uncertainty in velocity? Recall the formula for linear momentum.
END_HINT

ANS(num_cmp("$UvelocitySI"));

BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR
$PAR

b) If the ion has this velocity, what is its kinetic energy?

$PAR
$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(\times 10^{-13} \, \textrm{eV}\)

$PAR
$PAR

END_TEXT
BEGIN_HINT
Recall the formula for kinetic energy.
END_HINT

Context() -> normalStrings;

ANS(num_cmp("$energy"));


